'''Endodermic evagination''' relates to the inner [[germ layer]]s of cells of the very early embryo, from which is formed the lining of the digestive tract, of other internal organs, and of certain glands, implies the extension of a layer of body tissue  to form a pouch, or the turning inside out (protrusion) of some body part or organ from its basic position, for example the para-nasal sinuses are believed to be formed in the fetus by 'ballooning' of the developing nasal canal, and the [[prostate]] or [[Skene's gland]] formed out of evaginations of the [[urethra]]. <ref>{{cite book | last=Shipley | first=A.E. | title=The Shipley collection of scientific papers | series=The Shipley collection of scientific papers | issue=v. 151 | year=1911 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wt8zAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA269 | ref=harv | accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Esterly | first=C.O. | title=Some observations on the nervous system of Copepoda | publisher=The University press | series=University of California publications in zoology | issue=v. 3 | year=1907 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KCs-AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA269 | ref=harv | accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Rodeck | first=C.H. | last2=Whittle | first2=M.J. | title=Fetal Medicine: Basic Science and Clinical Practice | publisher=Churchill Livingstone | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-443-10408-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xzMeQbHJX0AC&pg=PA20 | ref=harv | accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>

